description.plain:
Ariana Grande (born Grande-Butera on June 26, 1993) is an actress and a pop vocalist from Boca-Raton, Florida. She had performed in many plays as a child but didn’t make a significant dent in her dream to become an R&B star until being cast as a cheerleader in the Broadway musical 13, earning a National Youth Theatre Association Award for her performance.

Soon after, she was able to land a role in the Nickelodeon hit TV series, Victorious, which propelled her to become a teen idol as her on-screen character seemed to be “very impressionable and easily swayed” but “generally sweet.”  From this point on, she was able to garner the fan base that allowed her to create tracks that worked only towards the promotion of the show, like “Put Your Hearts Up.”

She would have to wait until August 2012 to see the cancellation of Victorious, which allowed Grande to finally make music her priority. With her life now revolving entirely around this passion, she was able to release her debut album, Yours Truly: the result of a three-year endeavor. She completed the album, initially titled Daydreamin, in June 2013; it was released on August 19, 2013. In September 2013, it debuted at No. 1 on the US Billboard 200 albums chart, with 138,000 copies sold in its first week, making Grande the first female artist since Ke$ha to have her first album debut atop the charts.

On August 25, 2014, Ariana Grande released her second studio album, My Everything. Selling 166,000 copies in its first week, My Everything also debuted at No. 1 on the Billboard Top 200 chart. “The Honeymoon Tour” kicked off in February of 2015, and further promoted the album.

On October 30, 2015, Ariana released “Focus.” The song was initially intended to be the lead single for Grande’s 3rd album; however, it was removed in favor for the album’s title track. The song made an appearance on the Japanese release of the album. On May 20, 2016, Grande released Dangerous Woman, which became her first album to not debut at No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 200 chart, rather debuting at No. 2, selling 129,000 copies in the first week.

On February 3, 2017, Ariana started her second tour, the “Dangerous Woman Tour,” to promote the album. On May 22, 2017, during the Manchester Arena show, Grande’s performance was interrupted by a terrorist bombing. The tragedy killed 22 people and injured almost 800 people, and in June of the same year, Grande organized a benefit concert One Love Manchester to support the victims and their families.

Over two years later, Grande released her fourth studio album, Sweetener, on August 17, 2018. The album became her third No. 1 album and is her most acclaimed album to date. Sweetener gave Ari her first GRAMMY award for “Best Pop Vocal Album.”

On February 8, 2019, only six months after releasing Sweetener, Ariana released her fifth studio album, thank u, next, which included the Billboard No. 1 hits “7 Rings” and “thank u, next”, and the top five hit, “break up with your girlfriend, i’m bored.” The album contained themes surrounding female empowerment, denial, self-doubt, trauma, failed relationships, and a little bit of braggadocio.

Later that same year, Grande announced her role as co-executive producer for the Charlie’s Angels Official Soundtrack, released on November 1, 2019, featuring collaborations from Miley Cyrus, Lana Del Rey, Chaka Khan and more.

On the last day of her Sweetener World Tour, December 22, 2019, Grande released her sixth album titled k bye for now. The release marks her first live album, containing live versions of the original tracks from Sweetener.

description.plain:
On the lead single and titular track to her fifth studio album, thank u, next, Ariana Grande discusses themes of self-love, growth, and empowerment after a breakup. She also references her most public romantic relationships over the years and does not shy away from name-dropping in the process.

The song was released on November 3, 2018, minutes before an episode of Saturday Night Live aired. In a promotional clip, cast member and Ariana’s ex-fiancé, Pete Davidson, made a joke about the two’s failed engagement. Once she was made aware of the clip, she expressed her disgust in a since deleted tweet, writing:

for somebody who claims to hate relevancy u sure love clinging to it huh

She then followed her post with another, tweeting the phrase that would become her new mantra in 2018:

thank u, next

“thank u, next” debuted at #1 on the Billboard Hot 100, becoming Ariana’s eleventh top-ten entry and her highest charting single to date, surpassing her Iggy Azalea assisted single “Problem,” which peaked at #2 in 2014. Additionally, it was the first song by a lead female artist to debut atop the US charts since Adele’s “Hello” in 2015.

The music video for “thank u, next” was released on November 30, 2018, and is directed by frequent collaborator Hannah Lux Davis, who has previously worked with Ariana on videos for “breathin,” “Side to Side,” and more. The video interpolates iconic early-2000s movies Mean Girls, Bring It On, Legally Blonde, and 13 Going on 30, and features cameo appearances from celebrities including Kris Jenner, Troye Sivan, as well as Ariana’s former Victorious co-stars Daniella Monet, Elizabeth Gillies and Matt Bennett, among others. The music video became a huge success, accumulating more than 55.4 million views in its first 24 hours, becoming the biggest-ever global debut for a music video on YouTube. It would go on to break another YouTube record for the fastest video to reach 100 million views.

description.plain:
“7 rings,” which features Ariana boasting about money and many other luxuries, including diamonds and houses, is the second official single from Ariana Grande’s fifth studio album, thank u, next after Ariana announced that “imagine” will act as a promotional single for the album. The title is in reference to a collection of matching friendship rings Ariana and six of her friends bought in New York.

On December 1st, Ariana revealed the owners of the rings: herself, Victoria Monét, Courtney Chipolone, Alexa Luria, Tayla Parx, Njomza and Kaydence Krysiuk, all of whom have a writing credit on the song except Courtney and Alexa.

In December 2018, Ariana confirmed via Twitter that the “thank u, next” video featured a “7 rings” snippet, playing a loop of the instrumental at the beginning.

On January 12th, 2019, Ariana tweeted a very small snippet of the song, and then on January 14th, she posted a sneak peek for the music video on her Instagram. Two days later, Ariana uploaded a video of her dancing to the track in the car from 22 December 2018, with a timer counting down to the song’s release. This was also the first time any lyrics were heard.

description.plain:
“God is a woman” is the second single from Ariana Grande’s fourth studio album, Sweetener, which refers to the pleasures of sex and, consequently, encourages the message of female sexual liberation and domination. The track was teased in her “no tears left to cry” music video, and was hinted again in the “no tears left to cry (BTS – Part 2)” video.

Through her interview with Time Magazine, the track is described as an “anthemic, sultry banger.” The production is described as having “Grande’s voice layered so that it sounds like a choir, but really, is only her, multiplied.”

According to Ariana during an interview with Jimmy Fallon on May 1, 2018, “God is a Woman” is one of her grandma’s favorite tracks.

The track was speculated to be released on July 20, 2018, following Grande’s “20th of each month” release schedule for the album. At midnight on July 12th, Grande tweeted that she would be releasing the song and music video early as a surprise.

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1017257355560542208

description.plain:
“no tears left to cry” is a self-lifting anthem by pop songstress Ariana Grande. This is the lead single to her fourth studio album, Sweetener. It also marks Ariana’s return to music after a hiatus from performing in the wake of the 2017 Manchester bombing attack that occurred during her Dangerous Woman Tour.

After teasing the single through a series of photos taken of her wearing a sweatshirt with the lead single’s title and through her Instagram story, Ariana broke her social media silence to confirm the single via her twitter alongside with teardrop emoji, and stating: “missed you”.

For the single cover, Ariana looks on as a rainbow rests across her eyes. Rainbows are a natural phenomenon that appear after rain, as the sun refracts through the water droplets. Symbolically, a rainbow tends to represent the idea of hope and optimism. The image illustrates the idea that Ariana’s teardrops have faded, resulting in the rainbow, and she is ready to move on.

Her accompanying music video was teased on Instagram on April 19, 2018, and was officially published on Youtube the next day.

description.plain:
On “breathin”, Ariana opens up about her anxiety.

She revealed to Vogue that she’d “always had anxiety,” but that the events of the Manchester bombing gave her post-traumatic stress disorder.

I think a lot of people have anxiety, especially right now. My anxiety has anxiety… [but] I’ve never really spoken about it because I thought everyone had it, but when I got home from tour it was the most severe I think it’s ever been.

First teased during her “No Tears Left To Cry” music video, the song was alluded to again during the “No Tears Left To Cry (BTS – Part 2)” video, before being officially released on August 17. The song reached #1 on the US iTunes singles chart on August 19, 2018, and is expected to be announced as Sweetener’s third single soon.

A music video released on November 7, 2018 which contains words such as “Needy” and “Imagine”. These words are speculated to be the track-list of her upcoming fifth studio album.

description.plain:
In “break up with your girlfriend, i’m bored,” thank u, next’s final track and third official single, Ariana meets a boy at a party and is attracted to him, only to realize that he has a girlfriend. She tells him to break up with his girlfriend so Ariana can have him for herself.

In the music video, the girlfriend is symbolized as another version of Ariana. This indicates that she is breaking up with her boyfriend to start loving herself.

A snippet of the song was shared to tease the artwork of the album through a post on Instagram on January 23rd, 2019.

description.plain:
“imagine,” the first promotional single from thank u, next, is about an unattainable love that is “now and forever” unreachable. The track has been described to be the opposite of “thank u, next,” which has a central message of self-empowerment.

Although it’s not confirmed, the inspiration for “imagine” likely lies in the death of Grande’s ex-boyfriend Mac Miller, who passed away from a drug overdose shortly after the two parted ways. This could suggest the song is about the unattainability of their love now that Miller has passed. Many of the lines in this track also mirror Mac’s 2016 track “Cinderella”, which was confirmed to be about Ariana.

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1073027444838412289

The track was teased in the music video for Sweetener single, “breathin,” similar to what she had done before with the “no tears left to cry” music video.

Interestingly, Ariana continues to associate her music to her exes, as the cover art designer for the single was her ex-boyfriend and backup dancer, Ricky Rozay. He keeps it pretty simple, black and white with these characters on it – 想像. These translate to “imagine” in Chinese and to “imagination” in Japanese.

description.plain:
“pete davidson,” the fourteenth track from Ariana Grande’s fourth album, Sweetener, is personally dedicated to her ex-fiancé Pete Davidson to whom Ariana became engaged in June 2018. The song title was confirmed via Twitter.

https://twitter.com/arianagrande/status/1008507274984337414?s=21

In the track, Ariana explores the happiness and content she feels with the Saturday Night Live star. It follows her breakup from rapper Mac Miller in May 2018-  they were a public couple for nearly two years and split because Ariana perceived their relationship to be toxic.

On July 18, 2018, Ariana tweeted out a series of lyrics, followed by a wedding ring emoji, leading fans to believe them to be excerpts from “pete.”

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1019696036338655232

On July 28, 2018 the song title was changed from “pete” to “pete davidson.” Later, Ariana explained her reasoning for the change via Twitter.

Ariana wrote this song a week after they started hanging out, as she had told Jimmy Fallon on The Tonight Show:

https://youtu.be/7Wu-UMKSATc?t=183

Unfortunately, because of Ariana’s personal struggles, she and Pete called off their engagement and broke up on October 14, 2018.

In the track, Ariana explores the happiness and content she feels with the Saturday Night Live star. It follows her breakup from rapper Mac Miller in May 2018-  they were a public couple for nearly two years and split because Ariana perceived their relationship to be toxic.

On July 18, 2018, Ariana tweeted out a series of lyrics, followed by a wedding ring emoji, leading fans to believe them to be excerpts from “pete.”

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1019696036338655232

On July 28, 2018 the song title was changed from “pete” to “pete davidson.” Later, Ariana explained her reasoning for the change via Twitter.

Ariana wrote this song a week after they started hanging out, as she had told Jimmy Fallon on The Tonight Show:

https://youtu.be/7Wu-UMKSATc?t=183

Unfortunately, because of Ariana’s personal struggles, she and Pete called off their engagement and broke up on October 14, 2018.

description.plain:
On “Sweetener,” the titular track to Ariana Grande’s fourth-studio album, Ari talks about bad situations in life and how you can bring light and a positive vibe to  “sweeten” them. The track is very reminiscent of a 90s soul hip-hop song, but with elements of modern trap.

The track was teased in her “No Tears Left To Cry” music video, and was hinted again in the “No Tears Left To Cry (BTS – Part 2)” video.

This track was recorded and written back in July of 2016. https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1029146728065167360
It was the first song off the project to be completed.

Ariana had also posted an Instagram story, showing a screenshot of her listening to the track:

On July 21st, 2018, a paparazzi managed to record a snippet of the song while Ariana was listening to it in her car. She later confirmed it was indeed “Sweetener”:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1020747014886133760

On “in my head,” Ariana talks about how she fell in love with a version of someone she created in her head, to later find out that, in reality, that is not at all how that person is.

This track was first confirmed by Ariana on twitter, when a fan asked her if it was real, to which she replied:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1073275383175360517

Ariana’s Vogue Exclusive Cover Video of “in my head” was released on July 9, 2019, alongside her Vogue Cover: On Grief and Growing Up.

description.plain:
On “R.E.M.” Ariana Grande sings over a dreamy Pharrell-produced instrumental. She talks about how she does not want to wake up from a dream in which she fell in love with someone.

The track was teased in her “No Tears Left To Cry” music video, and was hinted again in the “No Tears Left To Cry (BTS – Part 2)” video. The song was officially confirmed through a Twitter post:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/990306560252395520

She also teased some of her lyrics by singing them acapella in ‘a Game of Song Association’ in her interview with Elle magazine.

She later confirmed on Twitter that “R.E.M.” is a song based on Beyoncé’s demo titled “Wake Up”, a leftover from the singer’s 2013 self-titled album, Beyoncé:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1023998130939813888

description.plain:
“Into You” is an uptempo, sexy, flirty track. It serves as the second single from Ariana Grande’s third studio album, Dangerous Woman.

This track was crafted by a certified team of pop hit makers—a team that’s churned out hits for Grande in the past. Super producer Max Martin and cowriting and production partner Ilya Salmanzadeh worked on this one with songwriters Savan Kotecha, Alexander Kronlund, and Grande herself. Most of them (in various combinations) also worked on “Bang Bang,” “Problem” and “Break Free.”

The song centres around an addictive love interest, possibly to her boyfriend at the time, Ricky Alvarez. The video was released May 23, 2016, and features Grande shacking up with a leather jacketed, motorcycle riding man (Don Benjamin).

Super producer Max Martin and cowriting and production partner Ilya Salmanzadeh worked on this one with songwriters Savan Kotecha, Alexander Kronlund, and Grande herself. Most of them (in various combinations) also worked on “Bang Bang,” “Problem” and “Break Free.”

The song centres around an addictive love interest, possibly to her boyfriend at the time, Ricky Alvarez. The video was released May 23, 2016, and features Grande shacking up with a leather jacketed, motorcycle riding man (Don Benjamin).

description.plain:
“the light is coming,” a promotional single from Ariana Grande’s fourth studio album Sweetener, is about relying on positivity to get you through hard times. Before its official release on June 20th, 2018, Ariana previewed it during her performance at Wango Tango on June 2nd.

This track was first teased in the music video for “No Tears Left To Cry,” and was hinted at again in the second part of the behind-the-scenes series.  Ariana once again teased the track at the end of her Billboard Music Award Performance, and on May 27, 2018, she posted a snippet of the song on social media. Later that day, Minaj teased the track by tweeting lyrics  from her verse. It was teased again when Ariana posted an Instagram story in which she seemed to be rehearsing for Wango Tango 2018.

Ariana’s collaboration with Reebok was promoted in the music video, and the video was even a Reebok.com exclusive for its first 24 hours. This is similar to how Ari’s campaign with Guess was promoted in the video for “Side to Side.”

The song draws heavy inspiration from Imogen Heap’s “Goodnight and Go.”, appropriating it for Sweetener by modifying the production and some lyrics. Ariana has stated on Instagram that Imogen was one of her primary inspirations as an artist, and made her who she is today.

description.plain:
Ariana described “Let Me Love You,” the second promotional single from 2016’s Dangerous Woman, as a slower, sexier, darker song. She stated it’s one of her favorite songs on the album. This is her first time collaborating with rapper Lil Wayne.

The song is rumored to be about her breakup with Jai from the Janoskians. Ariana confirmed on radio the song was the first track recorded for the album and was done “over a year and a half ago.” In the lead up to the song’s release, Ariana teased the song on Snapchat.

The official music video was released May 16, 2016 exclusively on Apple Music, and then worldwide on May 22, 2016.

description.plain:
On “Dangerous Woman"—a slow, edgy, pop-rock, R&B track—Grande revels in the excitement and power she feels when she’s with her man.

In an Instagram post, Grande revealed the title comes from Egyptian feminist writer Nawal El Saadawi’s 1975 novel Woman at Point Zero:

They said, “You are a savage and dangerous woman.” I am speaking the truth. And the truth is savage and dangerous.

In an interview with Billboard, Ariana explained that:

To me, a dangerous woman is someone who’s not afraid to take a stand, be herself and to be honest.

In February 2016, Grande retitled her album to “Dangerous Woman” from the original “Moonlight,” saying that it “represents more accurately where I’m at now.”

description.plain:
Originally, “Better Off” wasn’t supposed to be on Sweetener, but Ariana changed her mind and decided to add more songs to the album. Ariana revealed on Twitter that “Better Off” was the first song she added back to the album tracklist. She further reiterated this on an interview with Zach Sang that she wasn’t going to originally put it on the album in fear of its honesty of the relationship at the time and its potential to go south.

The song finds Ariana realising that a relationship isn’t for her and that she’s “better off without him” as she’d “rather [his] body than half of [his] heart”. Hence, to “steer clear of any headaches to start”, she “dismisses” his propositions.

It has been speculated the track is about Ariana’s former boyfriend, Mac Miller, a relationship with whom she’s previously denounced as “toxic” and the editor’s notes for the album on Apple Music express similar sentiments saying “ she exits a toxic relationship in “better off”.

description.plain:
“One Last Time” finds Ariana admitting to being unfaithful. Even though she knows she’s in the wrong and doesn’t deserve to get her ex-boyfriend back, she wants to spend one more night with him as her final goodbye. A part of her also hopes that after one more night together, he will be able to forgive her and take her back.

Rumour has it this song was written about Ariana’s affair with Nathan Sykes from The Wanted. Her boyfriend at the time of this affair was Jai Brooks from the Janoskians.

The chemistry between Ariana and her secret forbidden lover supposedly began brewing when they created the song and filmed the music video for “Almost is Never Enough” together.

After the Manchester terrorist attacks on 22 May 2017, Ariana’s fans redefined the meaning of this song and got it back in the charts to remember the 22 fans who sadly lost their lives at her concert that night.

description.plain:
The closing track off Sweetener was revealed through Ariana’s interview with Time Magazine’s Next Generation Leaders. The song has Ariana’s vocals interwoven in dense layers of sounds.

About the track, Ariana stated:

“I felt like I was floating for like 3 months last year and not in a nice way.”



The track is 5 minutes and 22 seconds long, paying respect to the Manchester bombing attack at Ariana’s concert on the 22nd of May 2017. There is also 40 seconds of silence at the end of the track, to commemorate those who lost their lives during the attack.

“The Way” is the highly successful, triple platinum certified lead single from Ariana Grande’s debut album, Yours Truly.

A month before its recording in January 2013, Grande hinted at the song by tweeting the lyrics to the hook.

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/284108203711660032

The beat was sampled from Brenda Russell’s “A Little Bit of Love”, also notable for its use in “Still Not A Player” by Big Punisher.

description.plain:
“make up” is the seventh track from Ariana’s 2019 album thank u, next.

The song lyrics consist of a constant play-on-words to intertwine relationships and cosmetics.

Ariana uses the word “makeup” to mean beauty products applied to the face  (usually enhancing one’s appearance), but it also refers to “making up” – as in forgiving and reuniting with somebody after an altercation.

description.plain:
“Problem” was the first single off of Ariana Grande’s sophomore album, My Everything. It’s an uptempo dance-pop/R&B song with a retro-feel thanks to its use of saxophone loops. The song features a spoken intro and a rapped verse by Iggy Azalea and uncredited, whispered-vocals on the chorus from rapper (and ex-Grande-flame) Big Sean.

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/456266453197418496

“Problem” received acclaim from music critics for its throwback sound and 90’s influence, with Rap-Up calling it an “infectious horn-heavy jam.” Grande told Billboard that the song “represents the feeling of being absolutely terrified to re-approach a relationship that’s gone sour – but you want to more than anything.” She also confirmed that the narrative is based on her relationship with an ex: “In the song, it ends on a sappy, negative note, but in [real] life, we’re hoping it’s going to end on a positive one. I feel like it’s all very honest and human.”

The song debuted at number three on the Billboard Hot 100, selling 438,000 copies in its first week and earning Grande her biggest digital song sales week ever. The song peaked at number two, surpassing “The Way” as her biggest hit single in the United States. “Problem” also made British chart history upon its debut as the first song to top the charts in Britain based on both sales and streaming. The music video won “Best Pop Video” at the 2014 MTV Video Music Awards, and the song itself won “Best Song” at the 2014 MTV Europe Music Awards. The song is featured in the video game Just Dance 2015.

description.plain:
“Focus” is all about ignoring the haters and looking for the good in all of us. It was the first single from Ariana Grande’s third album Dangerous Woman, but was later scrapped in favor of the title track and didn’t appear on the US version of the album (though it did make the Japanese and Target deluxe editions).

Ariana dropped a series of hints prior to the release, including a song snippet on Instagram and teasers on Twitter. Grande uploaded a vlog entitled “Focus” to her YouTube channel Honeymoon Diaries three weeks before the song’s release that spoke about its meaning.

I’m not asking to be the center of attention. […] I literally mean “focus on me,” on what I’m all about and what I believe in. The more we focus on each other, as people and not on what we look like, not what we’re wearing, our gender, our hairstyle, our sexuality, the color of our skin, but focus on each other on a soul level. The more we realize how much we have in common, the more we listen to each other, the more one we become.

description.plain:
“Everyday” is a sexually charged duet with rapper Future, and was released as part of her Dangerous Woman 10 day countdown on Instagram.

According to Ariana in a KIIS FM interview:

I knew I wanted to work with Future, but I didn’t know if we could find the right song to do together because we’re so different, but we found a dope vibe and it’s very unique and exciting.

The song was later premiered on Apple’s Beats 1 Radio, where she then announced the listening of a brand new track each day until the release of the album.

https://twitter.com/Beats1/status/730927671996088320

The lyric video was released on February 1, 2017, followed by the music video release on February 26, 2017.

description.plain:
Moonlight is a slow, violin-enriched track that serves as the intro to Dangerous Woman. It was originally intended to be title track of the album, but the album was ultimately renamed in favor of the track “Dangerous Woman.”

Last May, Ariana Grande announced that her third studio album was on the way and confirmed to fans via Twitter that its title was Moonlight.  During an appearance on Jimmy Kimmel Live! in January 2016, she announced that she changed the album title to Dangerous Woman.

From Digital Spy:

Grande eases you into her third studio album with this ‘50s-inspired sway, which blossoms with its dainty string plucks and romantic violins. But despite the twinkly production, which sounds like it was composed amongst the fluffy clouds in the sky, this isn’t reflective of what’s to come. Consider this Sandy Dee’s soaring ballad before she sexes it up with the black leggings.

Ariana posted a BTS video on Instagram of the filming of the “Moonlight” music video. The music video was ultimately scrapped following her breakup with Ricky Alvarez.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OFjs1JY954E

“raindrops (an angel cried)” is the introduction to Ariana Grande’s fourth studio album, Sweetener. This song is a cover of The Four Seasons' “An Angel Cried.”

The track was first teased in her “No Tears Left To Cry” music video, and was hinted again in the “No Tears Left To Cry (BTS – Part 2)” video.

The song was later confirmed by Ariana during her appearance on The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon on May 2nd.

description.plain:
“Be Alright” is a light, upbeat marimba-backed track. Ariana reassures her listeners that although we face challenges in life, eventually we’ll overcome our obstacles and “everything will be alright.”

This song first appeared on June 17, 2015, when Ariana released two separate snippets of the song on her Snapchat account, “moonlightbae,” hinting at the song for nearly a year up to its eventual release.

Ari performed “Be Alright” alongside “Dangerous Woman” when she hosted Saturday Night Live on March 12th, 2016.

Grande described Dangerous Woman as being “the only album [she’s] ever done where [she] loves each song just as much as the next.” She also commented on the album’s variety in a recent livestream:

Everyone who listened to this album so far has a different favorite and that’s amazing because it means my music is diverse. It’s hitting all parts of the soul.

She also went on to add that “this album is near and dear to [her] heart” and has “put [her] whole heart into this album.”

From Digital Spy:

Ariana’s breathy ad-libs glide over this deep house cut perfectly, as we’re all given a second for our heartbeats to slow down after ‘Dangerous Woman’. ‘Be Alright’ is subtly epic, by not feeling pumped to Ibiza proportions, but transporting you to a more mellowed state of euphoria.

A demo version of the song featuring Quavo and Takeoff of the Migos was leaked on May 30, 2018.

description.plain:
“Best Mistake”, produced by Key Wane is much softer than some of her other songs on the album, with Ariana laying down some smooth vocals and lyrics about previous relationships. Big Sean is featured here and is one of the few rappers on Ariana’s album. Sean’s verse is mainly a dialogue about someone in his life, and just how special they’ve become.

In fact, these lyrics turned out to ring true, after Ariana Grande and Big Sean began dating and eventually broke-up in April 2015.

The official video by Ariana Grande was then released weeks later on August 12th 2014 and primarily features Grande singing through extraterrestrial space scenes.

description.plain:
“borderline” is a track off of Ariana Grande’s fourth album, Sweetener, with a short but sweet verse by rapper Missy Elliott. The track was teased in her “No Tears Left To Cry” music video, and was hinted again in the “No Tears Left To Cry (BTS – Part 2)” video.

In an interview with The Fader, Ariana revealed that the track featured rapper Missy Elliott and was produced by Pharrell Williams, who has also produced other tracks off Sweetener. The song marks the first time Elliott and Grande have collaborated together.

On June 17, 2018, in response to a fan’s request for info on Twitter, Ariana teased the track with an ice cream emoji.

In a Livestream prior to the release of Sweetener, Ariana revealed that “borderline” was originally Missy’s track.

description.plain:
“My Everything" is the title track of Ariana Grande’s second studio album My Everything. Ariana first released a preview of the song on March 17, 2014 during a live stream.

Ariana said on a status update that she really wanted to name the album “My Everything” since the song was very special and honest.

The song is about how strong her love is for a past ex and how she deeply misses them.

Sadly, Ariana’s grandpa died on July 22nd, 2014 due to cancer. Ariana dedicated the song to him while on her Honeymoon tour.

description.plain:
Considered a sequel to her Mac Miller duet “The Way,” “Right There” is Ariana Grande’s sonic tribute to ‘90s R&B. The song was released as the third and final single from the singer’s debut album Yours Truly on August 6, 2013. Rapper Big Sean, who Grande would later date from 2014 to 2015, is featured on the track. “Right There” became a moderate success, peaking at #84 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart and was eventually certified Gold by the RIAA.

The song’s music video, based off the story of Romeo and Juliet, was released on October 30, 2013. Grande’s former Victorious co-star Elizabeth Gillies and actor Patrick Schwarzenegger make cameos in the video.

description.plain:
“Thinking Bout You” serves as the closing track for Dangerous Woman—the song features celestial production and a pulsating chorus.

Ariana sings about when your lover is away and you have to take care of yourself. The sense of longing and melancholy contrasts with the triumph of the last chorus. The album closes on a high note.

This is Ari’s self-pleasure anthem à la Destiny’s Child’s “T-Shirt” Selena Gomez’s “Cologne”, or Britney Spears' “Touch of My Hand”.

description.plain:
“Honeymoon Avenue” is the opening track from Ariana Grande’s debut album Yours Truly. Lyrics are believed to be about her ex-boyfriend, Graham Phillips.



“Honeymoon Avenue” was originally a working title for Yours Truly.

The original version of “Honeymoon Avenue” was more upbeat, similar to an Amy Winehouse song, while the official release is simply a remix, which sounds more like a Justin Timberlake/Timbaland-fueled track.

In an interview, Ariana spoke about performing the song live:

I almost cried last night when I was singing it onstage, ‘cause it’s about something that’s so special to me when I hear it. It strikes a personal chord. “Honeymoon Avenue” is about knowing you are at the end of a relationship and wishing it could not be the end and go back to the beginning and start over.

description.plain:
“Just a Little Bit of Your Heart” was written by Harry Styles, for Ariana Grande. Ariana was absolutely thrilled with the way the lyrics came out, stating in an interview for Eonline that:

The first time I heard it I was so like, touched, and moved, it was beautiful.

This sweet but anguished love-ballad showcases Ariana’s vocal abilities. The instrumental is primarily composed of simple yet powerful piano chords. The lyrics tell a sordid tale of a girl stuck in love with a cheating partner…who she simply can not let go off.

body.plain:
“Just a Little Bit of Your Heart” was written by Harry Styles, for Ariana Grande. Ariana was absolutely thrilled with the way the lyrics came out, stating in an interview for Eonline that:

The first time I heard it I was so like, touched, and moved, it was beautiful.

This sweet but anguished love-ballad showcases Ariana’s vocal abilities. The instrumental is primarily composed of simple yet powerful piano chords. The lyrics tell a sordid tale of a girl stuck in love with a cheating partner…who she simply can not let go off.

description.plain:
The penultimate track from American pop star Ariana Grande’s third album Dangerous Woman is split in two: “Knew Better” and “Forever Boy.” The two are starkly different in lyrical contexts.

“Knew Better” is a reflection of Grande’s feelings after breaking up with her ex. Whilst “Forever Boy” is a reflection of her relationship with her new boyfriend at the time. In between is a small musical interlude that smoothly transitions the two contrasting sides of love.

Fans demanded for a full verison of “Knew Better,” especially after being performed live on her Dangerous Woman Tour, and Ariana gave in an posted one onto an unofficial Soundcloud page  under the title “Knew Better Part Two”.

The two combined tracks were produced by Mr. Franks & TBHits, the latter of whom ended up producing her #1 smash “thank u, next”, and its follow up “7 rings”.

description.plain:
In “Santa Tell Me,” Ariana makes a wish to Santa Claus, pleading for him to not let her fall in love with her crush if they won’t be together in a year. She wants to make sure that the relationship is going to last before she puts her all into it.

In August, 2014, Grande ended her relationship with YouTuber, Jai Brooks. Two months later, in October, 2014, she confirmed being in a relationship with rapper, Big Sean. It is likely that “Santa Tell Me” is about Ariana’s hesitation at starting the new relationship with Big Sean, especially so soon after her breakup with Brooks.

She debuted the song during the A Very Grammy Christmas show.

The song is a bonus track on the Japanese edition of the Christmas Kisses EP, which was released on 3 December 2014. It is the EP’s fifth single.



Grande published the official video on her YouTube account on 12 December 2014.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nlR0MkrRklg

description.plain:
As part of her Twitter promises to release snippets of tracks off her album, Ariana let go of the Childish Gambino featured “Break Your Heart Right Back” on 8/14. In a recent interview with UK’s Metro she stated the meaning of the track:

There is a song called “Break Your Heart Right Back” which is about a boy that cheats on a girl with another boy. It’s one of my favorites on the album and it’s really funny because I believe it has happened to me. I’m not 100 percent positive but I’m 99.9 percent positive. I would rather he cheats on me with a guy than with a girl any day! If I found out my boyfriend was gay, I would be like “OK!” I’d be so relieved.

She also featured the track on a few of her Instagrams like here and here.

The song samples Diana Ross' classic “I’m Coming Out”.

description.plain:
“How I Look On You” is Ariana Grande’s fourth contribution to the Charlie’s Angels soundtrack. The song revolves around Grande questioning her love interest’s true intentions. More specifically, she wonders whether he is by her side for who she is as a person, or her fame and fortune, especially since he begins to distance himself from Ari, after he seemingly garners publicity.

Speculations have claimed that Grande took this opportunity to sneak diss her ex-fiance, Pete Davidson, with whom she had a short-lived relationship in 2018. Although no confirmation has been given on whether such claims are true, one could say that their heavily publicized fling and split align with the lyrics to this track.

description.plain:
“Jason’s Song (Gave It Away)” is a broadway influenced ballad, in which Ariana states that she will be strong and will maintain her voice, and no man or industry will stop her for being herself.

It was a collaboration between Grande and Jason Robert Brown, one of her earlier partners during her Broadway shows, such as 13.

It is featured on the Japanese & Target special editions of her third studio album, Dangerous Woman. It was eventually released to iTunes on September 15, 2016.

description.plain:
“Be My Baby” is the seventh track of Ariana Grande’s second album, My Everything and features the Norwegian DJ Cashmere Cat, who was also the opening act on one leg of her Honeymoon Tour.

Cashmere Cat also released an alternate version of this song on his SoundCloud.

Check out Ariana’s amazing live performance of the song below:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OTfiVnDiLKo

After much complaining from her fanbase, dubbed the “Arianators”, Ariana also agreed that “Be My Baby” should’ve been a single off My Everything.

description.plain:
“Baby I” is the second single off Ariana’s album Yours Truly. In this song Ariana Grande is trying to explain to the boy she loves him. Even though she has these strong feelings for him, she can’t get her thoughts and words together to express this to him.

Popsugar rated this track 4.5/5 and stated:

“Baby I” has a mid-’90s R&B diva vibe, with a smidge of ’70s disco energy — think Mariah Carey gone retro. Sure, Mimi is always the obvious comparison when it comes to Grande, since they both know how to tackle those octaves, but Grande does hold her own and exercises taut control over that voice of hers.

Ariana told Complex that Mac Miller encouraged her to release this as her second single and that the track was originally written for Beyoncé.

description.plain:
“Only 1” is one of three bonus tracks included in the deluxe edition of Ariana Grande’s second studio album, My Everything.

“Only 1” explains the delicacy of a love-struck young girl that is nearly in disbelief by how out of her league her boyfriend is. She is aware of the amount of other girls that virtually competed to be with him, and she expresses how shocked she is that out of a roster of other girls said boyfriend could have chosen, she is the lucky girl that has his heart.

This song, produced by Tommy Brown, unspools like the best kind of bonus-edition track: one that doesn’t quite fit in with the standard edition, but deserves the chance to be digested by the artist’s rabid fan base. Short, snappy and sumptuous, “Only 1” is a light confection that succeeds due to its busy, intricate percussion.

description.plain:
“They Don’t Know” is featured in Dreamworks' upcoming animated film, Trolls. The song is all about staying upbeat and happy with those who understand you in the face of a world full of haters.



Justin Timberlake, the executive producer of the film’s soundtrack and featured voice actor in the film, unveiled the song in the soundtrack’s tracklist on August 22nd.

The song is also written by Timberlake.

description.plain:
Ariana Grande teamed up with writers and producers Tommy Brown, Michael Foster, Steven Franks, Victoria Monet, Travis Sayles, Ryan Matthew Tedder and Peter Lee Johnson to compose her 2nd holiday EP Christmas & Chill.

On December 17, 2015, Grande surprised her fans by uploading snippets of the new holiday songs to her Instagram and Snapchat. Adding the cherry to the cake when she announced the EP would drop in just one day, December 18.

According to Ariana, the EP was recorded in one week in her home studio.

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/677584795988131840


 

Christmas & Chill consists of 6 original Christmas songs and was released through Republic Records.

description.plain:
“Intro” is an unreleased song which was intended to be the first song from Ariana Grande’s third studio album Dangerous Woman, titled Moonlight at the time.

On May 16, 2015, Ariana posted a picture through Instagram with the caption “baby loves, i’m tryna talk to you” 💭

She then tweeted more lyrics from the song:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/604295673207382016

She confirmed that the lyrics were for the intro song of her upcoming third album, not from the song “Moonlight” as fans thought:

https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/604296149709635585

Ariana eventually decided to use the song as an interlude on the Dangerous Woman Tour.

description.plain:
“Ridiculous” is an unreleased song by Ariana Grande, co-written by Miley Cyrus.

The song was first mentioned via MTV in 2013. It’s possible that it was meant to appear on My Everything, but it got scrapped. She claimed that Miley Cyrus came up with the idea in the shower, and then Grande turned it into reality.

In regards to the song, Ariana said, “It’s a great song—I love it.” She mentioned a “string sample” that would’ve prevented her from releasing it, however, it was later reworked and it was omitted from the final version that ended up leaking.

Grande also described the song as “really crazy” and “a bit all over the place”, then said, “It’s interesting melodically… It’s more like gymnastics. It’s like a weird melody and jumpy.”

On October 5, 2017, Music Mafia put the song up for auction, and it was sold at the price of 0.1BTC. It later leaked on October 22.

body.plain:
“Ridiculous” is an unreleased song by Ariana Grande, co-written by Miley Cyrus.

The song was first mentioned via MTV in 2013. It’s possible that it was meant to appear on My Everything, but it got scrapped. She claimed that Miley Cyrus came up with the idea in the shower, and then Grande turned it into reality.

In regards to the song, Ariana said, “It’s a great song—I love it.” She mentioned a “string sample” that would’ve prevented her from releasing it, however, it was later reworked and it was omitted from the final version that ended up leaking.

Grande also described the song as “really crazy” and “a bit all over the place”, then said, “It’s interesting melodically… It’s more like gymnastics. It’s like a weird melody and jumpy.”

On October 5, 2017, Music Mafia put the song up for auction, and it was sold at the price of 0.1BTC. It later leaked on October 22.

description.plain:
“reMeMber” was supposed to be a track off of Ariana Grande’s fifth studio album, thank u, next. The track was teased in the music video for “breathin,”, a single from her previous studio album, Sweetener

https://twitter.com/GrandeTourNews/status/1060217385930711045

It is speculated to be dedicated to Mac Miller, an ex-boyfriend of Ariana, who unfortunately passed away due to an overdose on September 7th, 2018.

The two ’M’s in the track’s title stand for his initials. Malcolm also has a track titled “REMember,” who he dedicated to his friend who passed away. Ariana also has another track on this album, “imagine,” which is dedicated to Mac and reflects many lyrics from his 2016 song “Cinderella.”

Due to Ariana’s decision not to release the song because she “wasn’t ready to share it with the world,” she released a track called “break up with your girlfriend, I’m bored” in place of reMeMber.

description.plain:
The debut single by Ariana Grande, “Put Your Hearts Up” was released on December 12, 2011.

Originally intended as the lead single for Grande’s debut album Yours Truly, it was later replaced by “The Way.” Grande later admitted that she “hated” the song and felt that it was a “terrible first impression”, naming “Put Your Hearts Up” “the worst moment of [her] life” and “straight out of hell” in a 2014 interview.

description.plain:
“Over The Rainbow” is a song by Judy Garland, which was featured on The Wizard Of Oz Soundtrack, as well as the movie. Ariana covered the song when she was only 14 years old, and re-performed the cover at the “One Love Manchester” show, following the bombing of Ariana’s concert in Manchester on May 22, 2017.

This live performance from the One Love Manchester benefit concert on June 4, 2017, was released as a single on June 6, 2017, and all proceeds will be donated to the UK Redcross Manchester Emergency fund, and all of the families affected.

description.plain:
A collaboration between Dua Lipa and Ariana Grande, recorded in January 2018. A snippet was leaked by Music Mafia on April 6, 2018.

During an appearance on ‘'Watch What Happens Live’‘ Dua said about the song they recorded back in January: “I love Ari, I love everything she does. But the timing wasn’t quite right.”

The track is titled ‘Bad To You’ and the singer went on to explain that busy schedules meant neither singer was able to go back and finish their parts for the potential collab.
